A x B represents the Cartesian product of sets A and B, which consists of all ordered pairs (a, b) where a is an element of A and b is an element of B. Similarly, B x A consists of all ordered pairs (b, a) where b is an element of B and a is an element of A.

A x B = {(1, 2), (1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 2), (2, 3), (2, 4), (3, 2), (3, 3), (3, 4)}
B x A = {(2, 1), (2, 2), (2, 3), (3, 1), (3, 2), (3, 3), (4, 1), (4, 2), (4, 3)}

The intersection of A x B and B x A, denoted as A x B ∩ B x A, consists of all ordered pairs that are present in both A x B and B x A.

A x B ∩ B x A = {}

There are no common ordered pairs between A x B and B x A, so the intersection is an empty set.
